Welcome to the most underrated part of design: space where nothing happens. Most beginners see empty space and panic. "Quick! Fill it!" But experienced designers? They leave it alone. Whitespace isn't wasted. It's working harder than anything else on the page.

Whitespace:

- Breaks up groups (like my teacher at the classroom)
- Shines a spotlight on what matters
- Makes your product look expensive (seriously, try it)
- Lets your eyes rest
- Makes text readable, not a word-salad

Cramped interfaces feel like rush hour. Spacious ones feel like someone cared enough to let things breathe.

## The Fear of Empty Space

New designers see blank space and get nervous. "It looks unfinished!" But the bravest thing you can do is leave it alone. Every beautiful, open interface you've admired? Someone fought the urge to fill that space.

## How to Handle Space

- If it feels crowded, add space before adding stuff.
- Start with more whitespace than you think you need. You can always tighten it later.
- Be generous with padding inside elements.
- Line height should be at least 1.5 times the font size for body text. More is better.
- Make space between sections way bigger than space between elements.

